322. Coin Change

You are given an integer array coins representing coins of different denominations and an integer amount representing a total amount of money.

Return the fewest number of coins that you need to make up that amount. If that amount of money cannot be made up by any combination of the coins, return -1.

You may assume that you have an infinite number of each kind of coin.

 

Example 1:

Input: coins = [1,2,5], amount = 11
Output: 3
Explanation: 11 = 5 + 5 + 1
Appraoch
1. If amount==0 return 0
2. if( idx==0) 
   if( target%nums[idx]==0 ) return target/nums[idx] 
4. perform take not take 
5.dp[i][j]= Math.min(t,nt) 
6. takes will store number of steps
7. return return dp[coins.length][amount]>=(int)1e9?-1:dp[coins.length][amount]

//Recursive
class Solution {
    public int coinChange(int[] coins, int amount) {
        int ans=help(coins.length-1,coins,amount);
        return ans>=(int)1e9?-1:ans;
    }
    public static int help(int idx,int [] coins,int amount)
    {
        if( amount==0) return 0;
        if( idx==0)
        {
            if( amount%coins[idx]==0)
            {
                return amount/coins[idx];
            }
            else
            {
                return (int)1e9;
            }
        }
        //nt
        int nt=help(idx-1,coins,amount);
        //t
        int t=(int)1e9;
        if( amount>=coins[idx])
        {
            t=1+help(idx,coins,amount-coins[idx]);
        }
        return Math.min(t,nt);
    }
}
  
